use strict;
use warnings;
use CAM::PDF;

sub extract_pdf_info {
    my ($pdf_file) = @_;

    my $pdf = CAM::PDF->new($pdf_file);

    my @pages = $pdf->numPages;
    my %info;

    for my $page (1..$pdf->numPages) {
        my $text = $pdf->getPageText($page);
        $info{page_$page} = $text;
    }

    # Extract specific information if needed
    # For example, to find the date or author, you might use regex or other techniques
    my $date = $pdf->getPageInfo(1)->{ModDate};
    my $author = $pdf->getPageInfo(1)->{Author};

    %info = (%info, date => $date, author => $author);

    return \%info;
}

# Usage example
my $pdf_info = extract_pdf_info('example.pdf');
print "Page 1: ", $pdf_info->{page_1}, "\n";
print "Date: ", $pdf_info->{date}, "\n";
print "Author: ", $pdf_info->{author}, "\n";
```

This script does the following:
1. It reads the PDF file and extracts the text from each page.
2. It also tries to extract the `ModDate` (modification date) and `Author` fields from the first page (you may need to adjust this based on your PDF structure).
